Here is the complete diagnosis and fix:

---

## Diagnosis

At viewports narrower than the `$elan-bp-sm` floor (672px), the existing rule in `layout.module.scss` correctly sets `overflow-x: auto` on `.contentArea` and `min-width: 672px` on `.contentAreaInner`. The intent is that only page content scrolls horizontally; the nav and footer (siblings of `.contentArea` inside `.siteWrapper`) stay fluid.

**The break at < 320px** happens because `.siteWrapper` — a flex column with `min-height: 100vh` and no explicit `overflow` declaration — does not itself become a horizontal scroll container. At a 200px viewport, the entire `.siteWrapper` renders at 200px. The nav renders at 200px too. `navInner` uses `justify-content: space-between`, so the right-hand link group is pushed toward the right edge and may be partially clipped by the viewport boundary. Because **no ancestor of the nav has `overflow-x: auto` scoped to include the nav**, there is no horizontal scroll track to reach the clipped items.

The `overflow-x: auto` on `.contentArea` only creates a scroll container for its own subtree (`.contentAreaInner` at 672px). The nav lives outside that subtree, so it gets no scroll coverage. With no document-level horizontal scroll either, the clipped nav item is completely unreachable.

## Root Cause

**AP-067 — "Min-Width Floor on a Root Wrapper That Contains Functional Chrome"**

The existing fix from FB-149 correctly avoided putting `min-width` on `.siteWrapper`, but it only solved the *content* side of the problem. It did not add any mechanism to keep the **nav's overflow scrollable** when the document renders narrower than the nav's minimum useful width. The scroll isolation was incomplete: `.contentArea` was isolated correctly, but the nav above it was left in a clip-and-no-scroll dead zone.

The deeper principle being violated: **functional chrome must remain reachable at every viewport width.** A nav item you can see but cannot reach (because it's clipped with no scroll path to it) is effectively broken.

## Fix

Three coordinated changes:

### 1. `src/app/(frontend)/(site)/layout.module.scss`

The `overflow-x: auto` on `.contentArea` must be promoted to also live on `.siteWrapper` in the narrow-pointer-fine range. This makes `.siteWrapper` the document-level horizontal scroll container, which means **both** the nav and the content scroll together horizontally if the viewport is narrower than the nav's natural minimum width. Simultaneously, the `min-width` floor on `.contentAreaInner` should be accompanied by the same floor on the nav, applied differently — the nav gets `min-width: 0` (already the default) but `.siteWrapper` itself gets the 672px floor so the *entire* page, including the nav, has a scroll-reachable minimum width.

```scss
@use '../../../styles' as *;

// ── ZERO RADIUS OVERRIDE ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// Portfolio branding: all border-radius is 0 on the public site.
// This overrides CSS custom properties so DS components (Badge, Card, Input,
// Dialog, Tooltip, etc.) all render with sharp corners when inside the (site)
// route group. Structural exceptions (Avatar, Toggle, Slider, ProgressBar)
// restore their radius locally in their own SCSS modules.
// See docs/design/branding.md §1 for the full rule.

.siteWrapper {
  min-height: 100vh;
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;

  --portfolio-radius-xs: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-sm: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-md: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-lg: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-xl: 0;
  --portfolio-radius-2xl: 0;
  // --portfolio-radius-full is intentionally NOT overridden.
  // Structural exceptions (Avatar, Toggle, Slider, ProgressBar) depend on it
  // for circular shapes. Badge pill shape should not be used on the portfolio —
  // always pass shape="squared" per docs/design/branding.md §1.2.
}

.contentArea {
  flex: 1;
  position: relative;
  z-index: 1;
  // Allow the flex child to shrink below its intrinsic min content width so
  // the overflow scroll container below can take effect at narrow viewports.
  min-width: 0;
}

.contentAreaInner {
  // Default: no width constraint — content fills contentArea naturally.
}

// ── DESKTOP MIN-WIDTH FLOOR ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
// On mouse-driven devices narrower than $elan-bp-sm (672px), the entire page
// shell — including functional chrome (nav, footer) — gets a 672px minimum
// width, and the DOCUMENT itself becomes the horizontal scroll container.
//
// WHY THE FLOOR LIVES ON .siteWrapper, NOT .contentAreaInner ALONE:
// Scoping the floor only to .contentAreaInner (the previous approach) creates
// a split scroll model: page content scrolls inside .contentArea, but the nav
// (a sibling) renders at the real viewport width with no scroll container
// covering it. At sub-320px viewports the nav items on the right edge become
// unreachable — they are visible on hover but there is no scroll track to
// reach them. This violates the core rule: functional chrome must always be
// reachable (AP-067).
//
// THE CORRECT MODEL: one horizontal scroll container at .siteWrapper level.
// The whole page shifts as one unit — nav + content + footer scroll together.
// Users get a single horizontal scroll track that lets them reach every nav
// item. This is the same scroll model used by GitHub, Figma Docs, and MDN at
// narrow desktop widths: the document scrolls, not an interior div.
//
// Scoped to `pointer: fine` so touch devices (which render at real device
// width, always ≤ 430px, with their own phone layout) are completely
// unaffected. See FB-147, FB-149, FB-225 and docs/design/responsive.md §6.10.
@media (pointer: fine) and (max-width: #{$elan-bp-sm - 1px}) {
  .siteWrapper {
    // The floor that guarantees every composed surface — including nav and
    // footer — has enough room to render legibly, and scrolls as one unit.
    min-width: $elan-bp-sm;
  }

  // .contentArea and .contentAreaInner no longer need their own scroll
  // container: they inherit the siteWrapper floor and stretch naturally.
  // overflow-x: auto is removed from .contentArea to avoid a nested
  // scroll container that would create two competing scroll tracks.
}
```

### 2. `src/components/ui/Navigation/Navigation.module.scss`

The nav itself requires no change to its structural rules — `position: sticky` correctly tracks within the document scroll container. But add an explicit comment so future agents understand why there is deliberately no `min-width` on `.nav` or `.navInner`:

```scss
.nav {
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;
  z-index: var(--portfolio-z-sticky);
  background-color: var(--portfolio-surface-terra-subtle);
  // No min-width here. The page-level min-width floor lives on .siteWrapper
  // in layout.module.scss (AP-067 guardrail). The nav must always be as wide
  // as its actual container — never wider, never capped with a floor of its
  // own. If the viewport is narrower than the nav's natural minimum, the
  // document-level horizontal scroll (from .siteWrapper's min-width) lets
  // users scroll to reach every item.
  box-shadow: 0 4px 12px -4px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);
  // ... rest unchanged
```

### 3. `docs/design-anti-patterns.md` — amend AP-067

Update the existing anti-pattern to codify the rule the user stated:

```markdown
<a id="ap-067"></a>
## AP-067: Min-Width Floor on a Root Wrapper That Contains Functional Chrome

**Status: ACTIVE — AMENDED (FB-225)**

**Trigger:** Placing `min-width` on a wrapper that contains both functional
chrome (nav, footer) AND page content, without also ensuring those chrome
elements are reachable via the same scroll mechanism.

**The inverse form (equally wrong):** Scoping the min-width floor to an
interior content wrapper only (e.g., `.contentAreaInner`) while leaving
functional chrome siblings (nav, footer) un-floored. At viewports narrower
than the nav's natural minimum, nav items on the right edge become visible
on hover but unreachable because no scroll track covers them (AP-067's
"clip-and-no-scroll dead zone").

**Why it's wrong:**
- A nav item you can see but cannot reach is functionally broken.
- The browser's native document scroll is the only universally reliable
  horizontal scroll mechanism. Interior `overflow-x: auto` containers work
  for content, but a sibling nav lives outside that scroll context.
- Splitting scroll contexts (content scrolls inside a div; nav does not
  scroll at all) creates an asymmetric, confusing experience where different
  parts of the page respond to horizontal drag differently.

**The rule:**
> **Never set `min-width` on the page root (`html`, `body`, or the outermost
> layout shell) without making that same wrapper the horizontal scroll
> container (`overflow-x: auto`).** If you need a min-width floor for
> composed surfaces, put it on the outermost shell — not on an interior
> content div — so the document scroll covers every element on the page,
> including functional chrome.

**Correct alternative:**
```scss
// ✅ Floor on the shell — one scroll context for everything
@media (pointer: fine) and (max-width: #{$elan-bp-sm - 1px}) {
  .siteWrapper {
    min-width: $elan-bp-sm;   // the floor
    // overflow-x is NOT set here — the browser document scroll handles it
    // naturally once siteWrapper is wider than the viewport.
  }
}

// ❌ DO NOT do this — floor only on content, nav left stranded
@media (pointer: fine) and (max-width: #{$elan-bp-sm - 1px}) {
  .contentArea    { overflow-x: auto; }       // creates isolated scroll track
  .contentAreaInner { min-width: $elan-bp-sm; } // only content scrolls
  // nav is a sibling → no floor, no scroll → right edge unreachable ❌
}
```

**Frustration caused:** FB-147 (initial min-width floor), FB-149 (chrome
isolation regression), FB-225 (sub-320px nav clip, the clip-and-no-scroll
dead zone). Three rounds.

**Related:** docs/design/responsive.md §6.10
```

### 4. `docs/design/responsive.md` — amend §6.10

Replace the current §6.10 block with the corrected model:

```markdown
### 6.10 Desktop Min-Width Floor — Shell Level, One Scroll Context

**Policy.** On the public portfolio site (`src/app/(frontend)/(site)/**`),
at `@media (pointer: fine)` AND viewport < `$elan-bp-sm` (672px):

- **The entire page shell** (`.siteWrapper`, which wraps nav, content, and
  footer) gets `min-width: 672px`. The browser document scroll becomes the
  horizontal scroll mechanism — users see a single horizontal scrollbar and
  can reach every element on the page including nav items.
- **There is no nested `overflow-x: auto` on `.contentArea`**. The previous
  two-container model (content scrolls inside `.contentArea`; nav stays at
  viewport width) created a clip-and-no-scroll dead zone for nav items at
  sub-320px viewports (FB-225). One floor, one scroll context.
- **Touch devices are fully unaffected** (`pointer: fine` guard). Phone
  layouts at ≤ 430px real device width render in the mobile composition
  as normal.

**The rule in one sentence:** the min-width floor must always be on the
outermost shell, never on an interior content wrapper, so document scroll
covers every element. (AP-067)
```

### 5. `docs/design-feedback-log.md` — append FB-225

```markdown
#### FB-225: "On viewports narrower than 320px, the fixed nav stops scrolling — clipped on right"

**UX Intent:** Functional chrome (nav) must be reachable at every viewport
width. A nav item visible on hover but unreachable because there is no scroll
track to it is effectively broken.

**Root Cause:** The previous min-width floor (from FB-147/FB-149) correctly
scoped `overflow-x: auto` to `.contentArea` and `min-width` to
`.contentAreaInner` to avoid the flash of horizontal scrollbar on the full
page. But the nav is a *sibling* of `.contentArea`, not a descendant — it
received no floor and no scroll coverage. At viewports below the nav's
natural minimum width (~320px), the right-hand nav items were clipped by the
viewport edge with no horizontal scroll track to reach them. This is the
"clip-and-no-scroll dead zone" variant of AP-067.

**Resolution:** Moved the `min-width: $elan-bp-sm` floor from
`.contentAreaInner` to `.siteWrapper`. Removed `overflow-x: auto` from
`.contentArea`. The document scroll now covers the entire shell as one unit —
nav, content, and footer scroll together at sub-672px pointer-fine viewports.
The split-context scroll model is eliminated.

**Pattern extracted → `design.md` §6.10 and AP-067 (amended)**

**Anti-pattern reinforced:** AP-067 — min-width floor on a wrapper that
contains functional chrome. New variant documented: the inverse form, where
the floor is scoped too narrowly (interior content only) and chrome siblings
are left stranded in a clip-and-no-scroll dead zone.
```

---

## Principle

**AP-067 (amended):** A min-width floor must live on the **outermost** shell wrapper — not on an interior content div. Scoping the floor inside a nested `overflow-x: auto` container correctly limits horizontal scroll to that subtree, but it leaves any chrome *siblings* (nav, footer) un-floored and un-scrollable. At sub-minimum viewports, those siblings clip and become unreachable — the "clip-and-no-scroll dead zone." The rule is: **one floor, one scroll context, on the outermost shell.** Document scroll covers every element by definition. Interior `overflow-x: auto` containers are only appropriate for data tables and other content regions that need independent horizontal scroll on viewports *above* the minimum floor.
